Run these as separate passes. Preserve behavior unless a specific bug is found.\n\n### 1. Deletion Pass\n\nLook for speculative generality:\n\n- one-use traits\n- one-use structs\n- generic helpers with only one real caller\n- parameters added for imagined future agents\n- fields that are always `None` or always the same value\n- comments that repeat the code\n\nDelete or inline when the call s\n[TRUNCATED]\nseparately before\nstarting cleanup. A cleanup pass should not hide pre-existing failures.\n\n### Step 1. Main Agent Reads The Code\n\nThe main agent should read the crate itself first:\n\n- `src/lib.rs`\n- `src/cli.rs`\n- `src/capture.rs`\n- `src/transcript.rs`\n- `src/gitmeta.rs`\n- `src/redaction.rs`\n- nearby tests\n\nThen follow one concrete command invocation from `but` into the crate. Keep this\nas a short call-chain note, not a design document.\n\nDo not spawn subagents yet. The main agent needs enough context to judge whether\nsubagent feedback is useful or just generic.\n\n### Step 2. Spawn Focused Review Subagents\n\nUse subagents for independent review, not implementation, at this stage. Give\neach subagent a narrow lens and ask for findings only.\n\nRecommended subagents:\n\n- **Deletion reviewer**: find fake extensibility, one-use helpers, dead fields,\n  ceremonial modules, and comments that repeat code.\n- **Boundary reviewer**: check that CLI, capture orchestration, transcript\n  parsing, GitMeta writing, and redaction stay separated.\n- **Execution reviewer**: follow `but agentlog capture` from CLI entry through\n  GitMeta write and report duplicated normalization, surprising validation\n  order, or side effects before validation.\n- **Rust reviewer**: check visibility, error boundaries, ownership/cloning,\n  naming, and idiomatic Rust.\n- **Test reviewer**: check whether tests protect behavior and whether any tests\n  are brittle implementation mirrors.\n\nOptional subagents:\n\n- **Security/privacy reviewer**, when redaction or transcript storage changed.\n- **Performance reviewer**, when parsing, redaction, or GitMeta read/write loops\n  changed.\n\nDo not ask subagents to rewrite files. Their output should be a short list of\nhigh-signal findings with file/line references when possible.\n\n### Step 3. Triage Findings\n\nThe main agent should merge subagent feedback into three buckets:\n\n- **Fix now**: behavior risk, privacy risk, confusing boundary, or easy\n  simplification.\n- **Document only**: useful future concern but not POC-sized.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T21:02:22.091Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}